{"title_page": "Bordesholm", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|image_photo       = Bordesholm Klosterkirche 01.jpg\n|image_caption     = Church\n|image_coa            = Wappen Bordesholm.png\n|coordinates       = {{coord|54|11|N|10|1|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan          = Bordesholm in RD.png\n|state        = Schleswig-Holstein\n|district             = Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde\n|Amt               = Bordesholm\n|elevation              = 32\n|area            = 10.16\n|population         = 7623\n|Stand             = 2007-1-18\n|postal_code               = 24582\n|area_code           = 04322\n|licence               = RD\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 01 0 58 022\n|website           = [http://www.bordesholm.de/ www.bordesholm.de]\n|B\u00fcrgermeister     = Ines Stelk\n|party            =\n}}\n\n'''Bordesholm''' is a town in [[Schleswig-Holstein]], [[Germany]] in the district [[Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde]]. ''Bordesholm'' is also the name of a former historical district of the [[Kingdom of Prussia]] and [[Weimar Republic]] for which it was the district capital. The '''district of Bordesholm''' was subsequently dissolved in 1932 and parceled out to neighboring districts (parts of the district of Bordesholm were joined with the [[Segeberg|district of Segeberg]] and the rest to Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde).\n\nThe town of Bordesholm developed around 1330, when the abbey of Neum\u00fcnster (founded in 1127 by Bishop [[Vizelin]]) was moved to an island in the Bordesholm lake.  Saint Vizelin was buried there. Thereafter, a village grew up at the shore of the lake, likely providing services to the abbey. Because of the abbey Bordesholm became the cultural and economic center of the duchy of [[Holstein]] (nowadays Schleswig-Holstein) region between [[Kiel]] and [[Neum\u00fcnster]].\n\nDuring the reformation the abbey was closed in 1566 by duke [[John II, Duke of Schleswig-Holstein-Haderslev|Hans the Elder of Slesvig-Holsten-Haderslev]]. It then became a Latin school, which was dissolved in 1665. The remains of the abbey and school library became the foundation of the library of the newly founded [[University of Kiel]]. 1773-1865 the area of Bordesholm was administered by the King of [[Denmark]] by the virtue of his being [[Duchy of Holstein|Duke of Holstein]].\n\n{{Cities and towns in Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde (district)}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde]]\n\n\n{{RendsburgEckernf\u00f6rde-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|image_photo       = Bordesholm Klosterkirche 01.jpg\n|image_caption     = Church\n|image_coa            = Wappen Bordesholm.png\n|coordinates       = {{coord|54|11|N|10|1|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan          = Bordesholm in RD.png\n|state        = Schleswig-Holstein\n|district             = Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde\n|Amt               = Bordesholm\n|elevation              = 32\n|area            = 10.16\n|population         = 7623\n|Stand             = 2007-1-18\n|postal_code               = 24582\n|area_code           = 04322\n|licence               = RD\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 01 0 58 022\n|Adresse-Verband   = Marktplatz<br />24582 Bordesholm\n|website           = [http://www.bordesholm.de/ www.bordesholm.de]\n|B\u00fcrgermeisterin     = Ines Stelk\n|party            =\n}}\n\n'''Bordesholm''' is a town in [[Schleswig-Holstein]], [[Germany]] in the district [[Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde]]. ''Bordesholm'' is also the name of a former historical district of the [[Kingdom of Prussia]] and [[Weimar Republic]] for which it was the district capital. The '''district of Bordesholm''' was subsequently dissolved in 1932 and parceled out to neighboring districts (parts of the district of Bordesholm were joined with the [[Segeberg|district of Segeberg]] and the rest to Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde).\n\nThe town of Bordesholm developed around 1330, when the abbey of Neum\u00fcnster (founded in 1127 by Bishop [[Vizelin]]) was moved to an island in the Bordesholm lake.  Saint Vizelin was buried there. Thereafter, a village grew up at the shore of the lake, likely providing services to the abbey. Because of the abbey Bordesholm became the cultural and economic center of the duchy of [[Holstein]] (nowadays Schleswig-Holstein) region between [[Kiel]] and [[Neum\u00fcnster]].\n\nDuring the reformation the abbey was closed in 1566 by duke [[John II, Duke of Schleswig-Holstein-Haderslev|Hans the Elder of Slesvig-Holsten-Haderslev]]. It then became a Latin school, which was dissolved in 1665. The remains of the abbey and school library became the foundation of the library of the newly founded [[University of Kiel]]. 1773-1865 the area of Bordesholm was administered by the King of [[Denmark]] by the virtue of his being [[Duchy of Holstein|Duke of Holstein]].\n\n{{Cities and towns in Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde (district)}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Rendsburg-Eckernf\u00f6rde]]\n\n\n{{RendsburgEckernf\u00f6rde-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bordesholm"}
{"title_page": "List of players who have scored 10,000 or more runs in Test cricket", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2018}}\n[[File:Sunny Gavaskar Sahara.jpg|thumb|[[Sunil Gavaskar]] was the first player to cross the 10,000 run mark in Tests.|alt=Sunil Gavaskar]]\nScoring over 10,000 [[Run (cricket)|runs]] across a playing career in any format of [[cricket]] is considered a significant achievement.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ugra|first1=Sharda|title=1987-Gavaskar is the first to score 10,000 test runs: A 10 tonne toast|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/1987-Gavaskar+is+the+first+to+score+10,000+test+runs:+A+10+tonne+toast/1/76385.html|work=[[India Today]]|date=24 December 2009|accessdate=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822133940/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/1987-Gavaskar%20is%20the%20first%20to%20score%2010%2C000%20test%20runs%3A%20A%2010%20tonne%20toast/1/76385.html|archive-date=22 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In the chase for achieving top scores, West Indian [[Garfield Sobers]] retired as the most prolific run scorer in [[Test cricket]], with a total of 8,032 runs in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Sobers: Cricket's greatest genius|url=http://cricket.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jul/28/slide-show-1-images-sir-garfield-sobbers-great-all-rounder-birthday.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=20 January 2013|date=28 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124043529/http://cricket.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jul/28/slide-show-1-images-sir-garfield-sobbers-great-all-rounder-birthday.htm|archive-date=24 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The record stood for nine years, until it was broken by England's [[Geoffrey Boycott]] in the [[English cricket team in India in 1981\u201382|1982 series against India]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/152249.html | title=Third Test Match&nbsp;\u2014 India vs. England 1981\u201382 | work=[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]] | accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W-MOwMxxxB0C | title=Head On&nbsp;\u2014 Ian Botham: The Autobiography | publisher=[[Random House]] | last=Botham | first=Ian | authorlink=Ian Botham | date=15 September 2009 | isbn=978-0-091-92149-1 | ref=harv}}</ref> Boycott remained the top scorer in the format until Indian batsman [[Sunil Gavaskar]] surpassed his tally two years later in 1983.<ref name=\"Most runs\">{{cite web | url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/223646.html | title=Records / Test matches / Batting records / Most runs in career | publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=21 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009085046/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/223646.html | archive-date=9 October 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Finlay | first=Ric | title=Record-holders for most number of Test runs | url=http://blogs.espncricinfo.com/itfigures/archives/2008/10/record_holders_for_most_number.php | publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=29 January 2013 | date=29 October 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722032321/http://blogs.espncricinfo.com/itfigures/archives/2008/10/record_holders_for_most_number.php | archivedate=22 July 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In March 1987, Gavaskar became the first player to cross 10,000 run mark in Tests during a match against [[Pakistan cricket team|Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Fastest\"/> {{As of|2017|05}}, thirteen players\u2014from seven teams that are [[List of International Cricket Council members#Full members|Full Members of the International Cricket Council]] (ICC)\u2014have scored 10,000 runs in Tests. Out of these, three are from [[India cricket team|India]] and [[Australia cricket team|Australia]] while two are from [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Sri Lanka]] and the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]]. One player each from [[South Africa cricket team|South Africa]], [[England cricket team|England]] and Pakistan form the rest.<ref name=\"Fastest\">{{cite web | title=Records / Test matches / Batting records / Fastest to 10000 runs | url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283191.html | publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]] | accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref> No player from [[Bangladesh cricket team|Bangladesh]], [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]], [[Afghanistan cricket team|Afghanistan]], [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]] or [[Zimbabwe cricket team|Zimbabwe]] has passed the 10,000 run mark in Tests yet. \n\nIn terms of [[innings]], West Indian [[Brian Lara]], [[Sachin Tendulkar]] and [[Kumar Sangakkara]] are the fastest (195) to reach the 10,000 run mark, while Australia's [[Steve Waugh]] is the slowest to achieve the feat (244).<ref name=\"Fastest\"/> Tendulkar holds multiple records\u2014most appearances (200 matches), most runs (15,921) and highest number of both [[Century (cricket)|centuries]] (51) and [[Half century|half-centuries]] (68).<ref name=\"Most runs\"/> England's [[Alastair Cook]] is the fastest in terms of time span, taking 10 years and 87 days, while West Indian [[Shivnarine Chanderpaul]]'s time span of 18 years and 37 days is the slowest among all. Pakistan's [[Younis Khan]] is the latest player to achieve this feat.\n\n==Key==\n* '''First'''&nbsp;\u2013 denotes the year of debut\n* '''Last'''&nbsp;\u2013 denotes the year of the latest match\n* '''Mat.'''&nbsp;\u2013 denotes the number of matches played\n* '''Inn.'''&nbsp;\u2013 denotes the number of innings batted\n* '''Date'''&nbsp;\u2013 denotes the date on which the player reached the 10,000 run mark\n* ^&nbsp;\u2013 denotes that the player was at some time the [[List of Test cricket records#RunProgression|leading run scorer in Tests]]\n* {{dagger}}&nbsp;\u2013 denotes that the player is active in Tests\n\n==Players with 10,000 or more Test runs==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ 10,000 or more runs in Tests<ref name=\"Fastest\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | No.\n! scope=\"col\" | Player\n!Portrait\n! scope=\"col\" | Team\n! scope=\"col\" | First\n! scope=\"col\" | Last\n! scope=\"col\" | Mat.\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Innings|Inn.]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Run (cricket)|Runs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Batting average (cricket)|Avg.]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Century (cricket)|100s]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Half century|50s]]\n! scope=\"col\" | Date<ref name=\"Fastest\"/>\n|-\n! 1 \n|{{sortname|Sachin|Tendulkar}}<ref name=\"Most runs\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/35320.html | title=Sachin Tendulkar &#124; Cricket Players and Officials | publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=22 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111231090501/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/35320.html | archive-date=31 December 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref> ^\n|[[File:SachinTendulkar4.jpg|100px|alt=Sachin Tendulkar]]|| {{cr|IND}} || 1989 || 2013 || 200 || 329\n! scope=\"row\" |15,921\n|| 53.78 || 51 || 68 || {{dts|format=dmy|2005|3|16}}\n|-\n! 2 \n|{{sortname|Ricky|Ponting}}<ref name=\"Most runs\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/7133.html | title=Ricky Ponting &#124; Cricket Players and Officials | publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=22 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826120911/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/7133.html | archive-date=26 August 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|[[File:Ricky Ponting 2015.jpg|100px|alt=Ricky Ponting]]|| {{cr|AUS}} || 1995 || 2012 || 168 || 287\n! scope=\"row\" |13,378\n|| 51.85 || 41 || 62 || {{dts|format=dmy|2008|5|30}}\n|-\n! 3 \n|{{sortname|Jacques|Kallis}}<ref name=\"Most runs\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/45789.html | title=Jacques Kallis &#124; Cricket Players and Officials | publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=22 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822075342/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/45789.html | archive-date=22 August 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|[[File:JAQUES KALLIS (3175901786).jpg|100px|alt=Jacques Kallis]]|| {{cr|SA}} || 1995 || 2013 || 166 || 280\n! scope=\"row\" |13,289\n|| 55.37 || 45 || 55 || {{dts|format=dmy|2009|2|27}}\n|-\n! 4 \n|{{sortname|Rahul|Dravid}}<ref name=\"Most runs\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/28114.html | title=Rahul Dravid &#124; Cricket Players and Officials | publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=22 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111231211258/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/28114.html | archive-date=31 December 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|[[File:Rahul Dravid at GQ Men Of The Year 2012 AWARD.jpg|100px|alt=Rahul Dravid]]|| {{cr|IND}} || 1996 || 2012 || 164 || 286\n! scope=\"row\" |13,288\n|| 52.31 || 36 || 63 || {{dts|format=dmy|2008|3|29}}\n|-\n! 5 \n|{{sortname|Alastair|Cook}}<ref name=\"Most runs\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/11728.html |title=Alastair Cook &#124; Cricket Players and Officials |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n|[[File:Alastair Cook vs Upminster CC.jpg|100px|alt=Alastair Cook]]|| {{cr|ENG}} || 2006 || 2018 || 161 || 291\n! scope=\"row\" |12,472\n|| 45.35 || 33 || 57 || {{dts|format=dmy|2016|05|30}}\n|-\n! 6 \n|{{sortname|Kumar|Sangakkara}}<ref name=\"Most runs\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/50710.html | title=Kumar Sangakkara &#124; Cricket Players and Officials | publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=22 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822143338/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/50710.html | archive-date=22 August 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n|[[File:Kumar Sangakkara.jpg|100px|alt=Kumar Sangakkara]]|| {{cr|SL}} || 2000 || 2015 || 134 || 233\n! scope=\"row\" |12,400\n|| 57.40 || 38 || 52 || {{dts|format=dmy|2012|12|26}}\n|-\n! 7 \n|{{sortname