{"title_page": "Horace C. Lee", "text_new": "'''Horace Clark Lee''' (January 31, 1822 &ndash; June 22, 1884) was an American [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] [[Brevet (military)#American Civil War|brevet]] [[brigadier general]] during the period of the [[American Civil War]]. He received his appointment as [[Brevet (military)#American Civil War|brevet brigadier general]] dated to March 13, 1865.<ref>{{cite book | author= | editor= | year= 1983 | title= The Photographic History of the Civil War: Three Volumes in One | publisher= Random House Value Publishing, Inc. | location= New York | id=0-517-20155-0 | pages= 314}}</ref>\n\nHorace C. Lee served as a colonel for the [[27th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]] during much of the American Civil War. Lee was born in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]], on January 31, 1822. Before the war, Lee had worked as a dry-goods merchant, an assessor, a collector, and a treasurer for Springfield, Massachusetts. At the age of 20, he enlisted as a private in the Springfield Light Guards. Upon formation of the Springfield City Guard Company, Lieutenant Lee was elected captain. On August 23, 1861, Governor [[John Albion Andrew]] offered him the position of lieutenant colonel in the [[21st Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]]. On September 20, 1861, he was promoted to colonel. He participated in the battles of [[Battle of Roanoke Island|Roanoke Island]] and [[Battle of New Bern|New Berne]] in North Carolina. Upon the departure of General Burnside, Lee was appointed acting brigadier general of the Trenton Expedition. General Foster appointed him provost-marshal general of North Carolina. In May 1864, he took command of the [[27th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|27th Massachusetts Infantry Regiment]] and fought in the battles of Walthal Junction, Arrrowfield Church, and Drewry's Bluff where he was captured and hence sent to [[Libby Prison]] in Richmond, Virginia, and Camp Oglethorpe in Macon, Georgia. He was freed in a prisoner exchange on August 2, 1864, and mustered out of the military a month later on September 27, 1864. After the war, he served multiple terms as the postmaster for Springfield, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite book | author= William P. Derby | editor= | year= 1883 | title= Bearing Arms in the Twenty-Seventh Massachusetts Regiment of Volunteer | publisher= | location= Boston | id= | pages= 34-36}}</ref> He died on June 22, 1884.<ref>{{cite book | author= Society of the Army of the Potomac | editor= | year= 1888 | title= Report of the Annual Re-union, Volume 14 | publisher= MacGowan & Slipper, Printers | location= New York | id= | pages= 99 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War}}\n{{clear}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Horace C.}}\n[[Category:1822 births]]\n[[Category:1884 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Massachusetts in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army colonels]]\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Horace Clark Lee''' (January 31, 1822 &ndash; June 22, 1884) was an American [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] [[Brevet (military)#American Civil War|brevet]] [[brigadier general]] during the period of the [[American Civil War]]. He received his appointment as [[Brevet (military)#American Civil War|brevet brigadier general]] dated to March 13, 1865.<ref>{{cite book | author= | editor= | year= 1983 | title= The Photographic History of the Civil War: Three Volumes in One | publisher= Random House Value Publishing, Inc. | location= New York | id=0-517-20155-0 | pages= 314}}</ref>\n\nHorace C. Lee served as a colonel for the [[27th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]] during much of the American Civil War. Lee was born in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]], on January 31, 1822. Before the war, Lee had worked as a dry-goods merchant, an assessor, a collector, and a treasurer for Springfield, Massachusetts. At the age of 20, he enlisted as a private in the Springfield Light Guards. Upon formation of the Springfield City Guard Company, Lieutenant Lee was elected captain. On August 23, 1861, Governor [[John Albion Andrew]] offered him the position of lieutenant colonel in the [[21st Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]]. On September 20, 1861, he was promoted to colonel. He participated in the battles of [[Battle of Roanoke Island|Roanoke Island]] and [[Battle of New Bern|New Berne]] in North Carolina. Upon the departure of General Burnside, Lee was appointed acting brigadier general of the Trenton Expedition. General Foster appointed him provost-marshal general of North Carolina. In May 1864, he took command of the [[27th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|27th Massachusetts Infantry Regiment]] and fought in the battles of Walthal Junction, Arrrowfield Church, and Drewry's Bluff where he was captured and hence sent to [[Libby Prison]] in Richmond, Virginia, and Camp Oglethorpe in Macon, Georgia. He was freed in a prisoner exchange on August 2, 1864, and mustered out of the military a month later on September 27, 1864. After the war, he served multiple terms as the postmaster for Springfield, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite book | author= William P. Derby | editor= | year= 1883 | title= Bearing Arms in the Twenty-Seventh Massachusetts Regiment of Volunteer | publisher= | location= Boston | id= | pages= 34-36}}</ref> He died on June 22, 1884.<ref>{{cite book | author= Society of the Army of the Potomac | editor= | year= 1888 | title= Report of the Annual Re-union, Volume 14 | publisher= MacGowan & Slipper, Printers | location= New York | id= | pages= 99 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Horace C.}}\n[[Category:1822 births]]\n[[Category:1884 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Massachusetts in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army colonels]]\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reference list duplication", "u